name: HTML to ZPL
description: Convert HTML/PDF to ZPL for Zebra label printers

api_methods.name: HTML to ZPL
api_methods.description:
Converts an HTML document to a ZPL label.

The HTML to ZPL API accepts 3 parameters:

- `height` a positive number denoting the height of the label, units are inches.
- `width` a positive number denoting the width of the label, units are inches.
- `html` the html content you want to render into a label. 
Note that HTML or body tags are not required. Think of it as just providing the contents to the body tag, anything that is valid in the body tag of an HTML document is valid here. You can also embed JavaScript inside the html parameter your pass the API

Upon a successful API call, raw ZPL is returned. You can save it to a file and print it, or you can send it directly to a networked Zebra label printer.

parameters.name: html
parameters.description: The HTML body that will be printed onto the label
parameters.default:
Hello World!

ZPL label generated by htmltozpl.com

parameters.name: width
parameters.description: The width of the label in inches

parameters.name: height
parameters.description: The height of the label in inches

parameters.name: dpi
parameters.description:
The Zebra printer resolution in dpi (dots per inch). Can be either `203`, `300`, or `600`.
The default value is `203` (used by most Zebra printers).

api_methods.name: PDF to ZPL
api_methods.description:
Converts a PDF document into ZPL code.

The PDF to ZPL API requires 3 parameters:

- `height` a positive number denoting the height of the label, units are inches.
- `width` a positive number denoting the width of the label, units are inches.
- `pdfBase64`  a *base64* encoded PDF file

The following parameters are optional:

- `rotate` - Rotate the label by `90`, `180`, or `270` degrees
- `scale` - scaling options to fit the PDF on the label (see below for details)

Make sure that the size of the PDF document matches the label size given in the width and height parameters exactly, otherwise some content might be cropped off.

Upon a successful API call, raw ZPL is returned. You can save it to a file and print it, or you can send it directly to a networked Zebra label printer.

parameters.name: width
parameters.description: The width of the label in inches

parameters.name: height
parameters.description: The height of the label in inches

parameters.name: pdfBase64
parameters.description: The HTML body that will be printed onto the label

parameters.name: scale
parameters.description:
Scaling/zooming options:

- `contain` - scales the PDF so that it fits entirely on the label, preserving the aspect ratio (no distortion).
- `cover` - scales the PDF so that it covers the entire label, preserving the aspect ratio. This can cause the edges to be cropped.
- `fill` - scales the PDF to the label, ignoring the aspect ratio. This can cause distortion if the aspect ratios don't match.
- `fitToWidth` - scales the PDF so that the width matches the label, preserving its aspect ratio.
- `fitToHeight` - scales the PDF so that the height matches the label, preserving its aspect ratio.

parameters.name: rotate
parameters.description:
The number of degrees to rotate. Must be one of:

- `0` - no rotation
- `90` - rotate right
- `180` - upside-down
- `270` - rotate left

parameters.name: dpi
parameters.description:
The Zebra printer resolution in dpi (dots per inch). Can be either `203`, `300`, or `600`.
The default value is `203` (used by most Zebra printers).
